  "prompt": "Why do secants have a vertical asymptote?",
  "response": "The secant function, denoted as sec(x), is defined as the reciprocal of the cosine function:\n$$ \\sec(x) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(x)} $$\nA vertical asymptote occurs when the denominator of a rational function is equal to zero, while the numerator is non-zero. In the case of the secant function, we need to find the values of x for which $\\cos(x) = 0$.\nThe cosine function, $\\cos(x)$, is zero at odd multiples of $\\frac{\\pi}{2}$, i.e.,\n$$ x = \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2} $$\nwhere n is an integer.\nFor example, when $n = 0$, $x = \\frac{\\pi}{2}$; when $n = 1$, $x = \\frac{3\\pi}{2}$; when $n = -1$, $x = -\\frac{\\pi}{2}$, and so on.\nAt these values of x, $\\cos(x) = 0$, so the secant function is undefined. As x approaches these values, the cosine function gets closer and closer to 0. Therefore, the secant function approaches either positive or negative infinity.\nSpecifically, as x approaches $\\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2}$ from the left, $\\cos(x)$ can be positive or negative, and as x approaches $\\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2}$ from the right, $\\cos(x)$ can also be positive or negative.\nFor example:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item As $x \\to \\frac{\\pi}{2}^-$, $\\cos(x) \\to 0^+$, so $\\sec(x) \\to +\\infty$.\n    \\item As $x \\to \\frac{\\pi}{2}^+$, $\\cos(x) \\to 0^-$, so $\\sec(x) \\to -\\infty$.\n    \\item As $x \\to \\frac{3\\pi}{2}^-$, $\\cos(x) \\to 0^-$, so $\\sec(x) \\to -\\infty$.\n    \\item As $x \\to \\frac{3\\pi}{2}^+$, $\\cos(x) \\to 0^+$, so $\\sec(x) \\to +\\infty$.\n\\end{itemize}\nThus, the secant function has vertical asymptotes at $x = \\frac{(2n+1)\\pi}{2}$ for any integer n.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{because sec(x) = 1/cos(x) and cos(x) = 0 at x = (2n+1)\u03c0/2}$",
